<TEXT>
federal legislation should not preempt state 
law on oil spills senate democratic leader george mitchell and 
three state attorneys general argued friday 
preempting our state law and requiring us to rely on a 
system administered by the federal government is not a proposal 
which can be accepted by the state of maine maine attorney 
general james e tierney said in testimony before a subcommittee of 
the senate committee on environment and public works 
mitchell dmaine pledged that there will be no federal 
legislation that preempts state law 
transportation secretary samuel k skinner testifying before 
the subcommittee on environmental protection stressed that the 
bush administration favors strengthening us law and supporting 
ratification of two international treaties or protocols to 
provide compensation for cleanup and damages resulting from oil 
spills caused by foreign tankers 
to argue that state laws offer a viable alternative to the 
protocols is to ignore the facts skinner said 
the treaties he said offer advantages not obtainable under 
state law such as the enforceability of us judgments abroad and 
consistency of limits and costs of shipowners and oil companies 
americans should not have to suffer all the costs of oil 
pollution caused by foreign tankers when an international system 
exists to pay for cleanup and damages skinner said a vote for 
the protocols is a vote for the environment 
tierney disagreed 
a vote for the protocols is not a vote for the environment 
he said 
also opposing the protocols were alaska attorney general douglas 
b baily and washington attorney general kenneth o eikenberry 
even if coupled with an international fund the result would 
be that in some situations damages would go uncompensated because 
state law protection is unavailable baily said 
kenneth r dickerson an arco oil co senior vice president 
told the panel that his company supports giving the federal 
government the sole responsibility for oilspill cleanups 
skinners testimony came as 17 members of the california 
delegation called on interior secretary manuel lujan to resign as 
head of a presidential task force studying offshore drilling 
recent comments indicate he has already decided to proceed 
with offshore oil drilling out of fairness he must step down 
said rep george miller dcalif 
lujan told a recent meeting of the western governors association 
the renewed oneyear ban on offshore drilling in many areas 
approved by the house was a dangerous course that would 
increase reliance on foreign oil 
the california group said it was deeply disturbed by the 
comments but lujans spokesman steve goldstein said friday 
the secretary does not plan to resign from the task force 
</TEXT>
