formerly served in koevoet a counterinsurgency force active in the 
23year bush war against guerrillas of swapo the southwest africa 
peoples organization many koevoet members were expert trackers 
police have reported the arrest of 30 suspected poachers in the 
past six weeks but wildlife experts say stronger measures are 
needed to halt the smuggling of ivory and rhino horns out of 
namibia 
according to the south africanbased rhino and elephant 
foundation at least 11 black rhinos and 30 elephants have been 
killed by poachers in namibia since june the black rhino is one of 
the most endangered species of large mammals with only about 3500 
believed to exist worldwide 
two months ago namibian conservationists began an unprecedented 
experimental program to deter rhino poachers by removing the horns 
of some of the animals the horns can earn thousands of dollars for 
smugglers from buyers in asia who use them to make potions and 
dagger handles 
